<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1436,535,1242]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,326,535,561]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Observations:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1982" box="[335,578,536,561]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cranwelli">
<emphasis box="[335,578,536,561]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Liolaemus cranwelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most controversial species of the genus, mainly because it was established on the basis of a single male museum specimen (
<bibRefCitation author="Donoso-Barros" box="[953,1220,576,602]" firstAuthor="Donoso-Barros" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="132 - 134" refId="ref58210" refString="Donoso-Barros, R. (1973 a) Un nuevo saurio de Bolivia (Lacertilia, Iguanidae). Neotropica, 19, 132 - 134." type="journal article" year="1973" yearSuffix="a">Donoso-Barros 1973a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge, R." box="[1235,1424,576,602]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref59302" refString="Etheridge, R. (2000) A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae), and a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs, 14, 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge 2000</bibRefCitation>
). There is no information on the living colour pattern of the species and the female is entirely unknown. Over the last decade, the debate on the validity of this species has increased (
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge, R." box="[993,1178,656,682]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref59302" refString="Etheridge, R. (2000) A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae), and a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs, 14, 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge 2000</bibRefCitation>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge &amp; Espinoza" firstAuthor="Etheridge" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref59521" refString="Etheridge, R &amp; Espinoza, R. E. (2000) Taxonomy of the Liolaeminae (Squamata: Iguania: Tropiduridae) and a semiannotated bibliography. Smithsonian Herpetological Information Service, 126, 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge &amp; Espinoza 2000</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge, R." box="[349,547,696,722]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref59302" refString="Etheridge, R. (2000) A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae), and a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs, 14, 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge (2000)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1982" box="[729,870,696,721]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cranwelli">
<emphasis box="[729,870,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">L. cranwelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Etheridge" authorityYear="2000" box="[1137,1304,696,721]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wiegmannii">
<emphasis box="[1137,1304,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">L. wiegmannii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, further studies are needed to clarify the problem. Unfortunately, because it is currently unfeasible to gather information on the variation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1982" box="[600,741,776,801]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cranwelli">
<emphasis box="[600,741,776,801]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">L. cranwelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, powerful conclusions might not be possible yet.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1436,535,1242]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
Additionally, it is necessary to clarify some aspects concerning the exact type locality of this species. In his monograph, 
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge, R." box="[343,544,856,882]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref59302" refString="Etheridge, R. (2000) A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae), and a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs, 14, 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge (2000)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that the only known specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1982" box="[1093,1236,856,881]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cranwelli">
<emphasis box="[1093,1236,856,881]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">L. cranwelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in “Macho Moka, 
<collectingRegion box="[337,470,896,922]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[482,574,896,922]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”, and that the distribution of this taxon would be “about 
<quantity box="[1244,1333,896,922]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="km" value="470.0">470 km</quantity>
north of the Sierra de Santa Bárbara....., from Macho, Nueva Moka, in the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[1139,1275,936,962]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,243,976,1002]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”. However, this information is partially misleading, because “Macho” is not a geographical point, but the Spanish word “male”. In the original publication, 
<bibRefCitation author="Donoso-Barros" box="[833,1117,1016,1042]" firstAuthor="Donoso-Barros" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="132 - 134" refId="ref58210" refString="Donoso-Barros, R. (1973 a) Un nuevo saurio de Bolivia (Lacertilia, Iguanidae). Neotropica, 19, 132 - 134." type="journal article" year="1973" yearSuffix="a">Donoso-Barros (1973a)</bibRefCitation>
detailed “Holotipo: 3632 M.A.C.N. Macho, Nueva Moka, 
<collectingRegion box="[543,677,1056,1082]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[690,782,1056,1082]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”, which really means “ 
<typeStatus box="[1054,1170,1056,1082]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Holotype</typeStatus>
: 3632 M.A.C.N. Male [individual], [collected in] Nueva Moka, 
<collectingRegion box="[634,766,1096,1122]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[778,870,1096,1122]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”. Consequently, the type locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laurent" authorityYear="1982" box="[1294,1436,1096,1121]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cranwelli">
<emphasis box="[1294,1436,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">L. cranwelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is “Nueva Moka, 
<collectingRegion box="[358,490,1136,1162]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[503,595,1136,1162]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”, and the proposed distribution provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Etheridge, R." box="[1116,1315,1136,1162]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref59302" refString="Etheridge, R. (2000) A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae), and a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs, 14, 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">Etheridge (2000)</bibRefCitation>
should be “about 
<quantity box="[237,326,1176,1202]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="km" value="470.0">470 km</quantity>
north of the Sierra de Santa Bárbara....., from Nueva Moka, in the department of 
<collectingRegion box="[1298,1432,1176,1202]" country="Bolivia" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
, southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[305,397,1216,1242]" name="Bolivia" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
”.
</paragraph>
